<subsection xml:id="subsec-magnitudes-of-vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Magnitudes of Vectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p>
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                        <p>Work out magnitude of a vector in different situations</p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
            <li component="lesson-plan">Grade Level: 10</li>
            <li component="lesson-plan">Estimated Duration: 40 minutes</li>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>Know</title>
                        <p>The magnitude of a vector is calculated using the Pythagorean theorem: <m>|\mathbf{AB}| = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Do</title>
                        <p>Plot vectors on a coordinate plane, measure lengths, and apply the magnitude formula to calculate <m>|\mathbf{v}|</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Apply</title>
                        <p>Use vector magnitudes to solve real-life distance and navigation problems.</p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/magnitudes-of-vectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_magnitudes-of-vectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Anchor Activity — Discovering Vector Magnitudes</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Objective:</em> Students plot points, draw vectors, measure lengths with a ruler,
            and discover the relationship between horizontal displacement, vertical displacement,
            and vector magnitude using the Pythagorean theorem.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>What is the horizontal displacement from <m>O</m> to <m>A</m>?</li>
                <li>What is the vertical displacement from <m>O</m> to <m>A</m>?</li>
                <li>What is the measured length of <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m>?</li>
                <li>Do you see a pattern? Does <m>3^2 + 4^2</m> equal the length squared?</li>
                <li>What mathematical theorem does this remind you of?</li>
                <li>How can we calculate the length of any vector if we know its horizontal and vertical components?</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Circulate among students, ensuring they plot points correctly and measure accurately.</li>
                <li>Ask probing questions: <q>What is the length you measured? How does it relate to 3 and 4?</q></li>
                <li>For struggling students: <q>Let us check together. <m>3^2 = 9</m>, <m>4^2 = 16</m>. What is <m>9 + 16</m>?</q></li>
                <li>For early finishers: <q>Can you try another vector, say from <m>O</m> to <m>B(5,12)</m>? What is its magnitude?</q></li>
                <li>Guide students to articulate: <q>The length of the vector is the square root of the sum of the squares of its components.</q></li>
                <li>Identify 2–3 students with clear findings to share with the class.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_p904w2rb">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_l9x8ksz4">
            <p xml:id="auto_62jbto3d">
               <alert> Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_cmbv3s1p">
                <alert>What you require: </alert> Graph paper
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_r65j85rd">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6juc9kwl">
                    Draw the <m>x</m> axis and <m>y</m> axis on the graph paper.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_61jc28cp">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_c6virc91">
                    Mark the coordinate <m>(0,0)</m> as the initial point <m>O</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_ovrfv1mk">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_esfrs2px">
                    From Point <m>O</m>, move <m>3</m> units to the <alert>right</alert> along 
                    the <m>x</m> axis and <m>4</m> units upward in the <m>y</m> axis.
                     Mark this new position as Point <m>A</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_c67doy3i">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ke43dhd8">
                    Draw a directed line from point <m>O</m> to point <m>A</m> to represent <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_nfylhtuw">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_mcpkpzob">
                    Use a ruler to measure the length of <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_bgbdxnzd">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_738xg9pv">
                    Analyze the relationship between the <m>x</m> displacement, 
                    <m>y</m> displacement, and the length of <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_ma9tml6u">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_jx2ebqgn">
                    Discuss and share your findings with your classmates in the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_ufv3puvt">
        <p xml:id="auto_vpc3z777">
            The <alert>magnitude</alert> of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> in 
            <xref ref="magnitude-vect-1"/> can be denoted as <m>|\mathbf{AB}|</m>.
            The magnitude of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> represents the distance between
            point <m>\text{A}</m> and point <m>\text{B}</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8ml9bqro">
            We can represent the components of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> as 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}</m>, where 
            <m>x</m> represents the horizontal displacement and <m>y</m> 
            represents the vertical displacement.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_95lke3kg">
            We determine the magnitude of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>
            by applying <alert>Pythagorean theorem</alert> as shown below.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m14586mw">
            <me>
                |\mathbf{AB}| =  \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}
            </me>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="magnitude-vect-1">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-2,-2) grid (6,7);
                        \draw[step=1cm,black!40,thick] (-2,-2) grid (6,7);

                        % Draw x and y axes
                        \draw[- &gt;] (-2,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x \,\, axis$};
                        \draw[- &gt;] (0,-2) -- (0,6) node[above] {$y \,\, axis$};
                        
                        \foreach \x in {-1,1,2,3,4,5}{
                            \draw(\x,0.15)--(\x,-0.15) node[below] {\x};
                        }
                            
                        \foreach \y in {-1,1,2,3,4,5}{
                            \draw(0.15,\y)--(-0.15,\y) node[left] {\y};
                        }
                        \node[below,left] at (-0.01,-0.2) {0};
                        % Define points
                        \coordinate (A) at (1,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (4,5);
                        \coordinate (C) at (4,1);

                        % Draw vector
                        \draw[very thick](A)-- (B);
                        \draw[thin,dashed] (A) -- (C) node[midway, below] {\small $x$};
                        \draw[thin,dashed] (C) -- (B) node[midway, right] {\small $y$};

                        % Draw vector
                        \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (1,1) -- (2.8,3.4); 
                        
                        %draw the right angle
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[draw=black,size=.2](A,C,B);

                        % Labels
                        \node[left] at (A) {$A$};
                        \node[above] at (B) {$B$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <!-- <p xml:id="auto_chourd6q">
            We use pythagorean formula to find the magnitude of a column vector.
            A vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> represented as 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}x \\ y \end{pmatrix}</m> where <m>x</m> is the horizontal
            displacement and <m>y</m> is vertical displacement, we find its magnitude by 
            applying <m>\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}</m>.
        </p> -->
        <p xml:id="auto_djp0v50j">
            The magnitude of a vector is always <alert>positive</alert>
            since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> components are squared, 
            resulting in <m>x^2</m> and <m>y^2</m>, both of which are <alert>non-negative</alert>.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students share their findings, formalise the concept of vector magnitude.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies — Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Misconception</cell>
                    <cell>Clarification</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Magnitude can be negative.</cell>
                    <cell>Magnitude is always positive or zero because we square the components.</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Just add <m>x + y</m> to get magnitude.</cell>
                    <cell>You must square each component, add them, then take the square root.</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>The order of squaring matters.</cell>
                    <cell><m>x^2 + y^2 = y^2 + x^2</m> (addition is commutative).</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>I do not need a calculator.</cell>
                    <cell>For most problems you will need a calculator to find the square root.</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Work through the textbook examples on the board, inviting students to supply each step.
            After the worked examples, assign the practice exercises for independent or pair work.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_y0no05r5">
        <statement>
            <figure xml:id="magnitude-of-vect">
                <caption></caption>
                <image width="45%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="magnitude-of-vectors">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                            % Draw x and y axes
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};

                            % Define points
                            \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                            \coordinate (B) at (3,4);
                            \coordinate (C) at (3,0);

                            % Draw triangle
                            \draw[very thick](A)-- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                            % Draw vector
                            \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (1.49,2) -- (1.55,2.1); 

                            % Right angle marker
                            \draw[very thick](C) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                            % Labels
                            \node[left] at (-0.02,0.2) {$A$};
                            \node[right] at (B) {$B$};
                            \node[below] at (C) {$C$};
                            \node[below] at (1.5,0) {$7$};
                            \node[right] at (3,2) {$24$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_dl8618g2">
                To find the magnitude of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>, we apply pythagora's theorem to find the length <m>\textbf{AB}</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_2kht0qka">
                <md>
                    <mrow> |\textbf{AB}| \amp = \sqrt{\text{(AC)}^2 + \text{(CB)}^2 } </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{7^2 + 24^2} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{49 + 576}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{625}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 25 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0ud75tmo">
                Hence, the magnitude of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> represented as <m>|\textbf{AB}|</m> is <m>25.</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_o67wmuxo">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_krwpkb89">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_isgaruio">
                Given that <m>a=\binom{2}{4}</m>, <m>b=\binom{-2}{2.5}</m>, <m>c=\binom{6}{-4}</m> and <m>r=a+2b-c</m>. Find <m>|r|</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_xl9bvgkc">
                <m>r=a+2b-c</m>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_stj3fujj">
                Substituting the values of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> into the equation;
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_7udyz6to">
                <m>r=\binom{2}{4}+ 2\binom{-2}{2.5}-\binom{6}{-4}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_k2ays5ai">
                <m>r=\binom{2}{4}+ \binom{-4}{5}-\binom{6}{-4}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_z56pc0vu">
                <m>r=\binom{2+(-4)-6}{4+5-(-4)}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_0cs7cwyg">
                <m>r=\binom{-8}{13}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_6vwrvpnn">
                <m>|r|=\sqrt{(-8)^2+13^2}=\sqrt{64+169}=\sqrt{233}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_zsiyavl2">
                <m>r=15.26</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Exit Ticket</alert> — Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>Find the magnitude of vector <m>\begin{pmatrix} -5 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
                <li>A vector has horizontal displacement <m>9</m> and vertical displacement <m>12</m>. What is its magnitude?</li>
                <li>If <m>\mathbf{p} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{q} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}</m>, find the magnitude of <m>\mathbf{p} + \mathbf{q}</m>.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li><m>\sqrt{(-5)^2 + 12^2} = \sqrt{25 + 144} = \sqrt{169} = 13</m></li>
                <li><m>\sqrt{9^2 + 12^2} = \sqrt{81 + 144} = \sqrt{225} = 15</m></li>
                <li><m>\mathbf{p} + \mathbf{q} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}</m>, so <m>|\mathbf{p} + \mathbf{q}| = \sqrt{5^2 + (-1)^2} = \sqrt{26} \approx 5.10</m></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-magnitude-of-vectors">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_3n78tnts">
            <p xml:id="auto_gdgfujjc">
                <!-- Find the magnitude of each of the following vectors: -->
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_e6ef5c8v">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_vrifgqwt">
                    Find the magnitude of each of the following vectors:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_flt3iqid">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_fd7uzo80" marker="(a)" cols="4"> 
                        <li xml:id="auto_b19yqboz">
                            <p xml:id="auto_qdxl65jj">
                                <m>\left( \begin{matrix} -6 \\ 8 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4vxmuc95">
                            <p xml:id="auto_iex0urqu">
                                <m>\left( \begin{matrix}  8 \\ 15 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_mvdpedw3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_yo4hes8g">
                                <m>\left( \begin{matrix}  -5 \\ 12 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_erx03w9t">
                            <p xml:id="auto_p0hebdxg">
                                <m>\left( \begin{matrix}  3 \\ 7 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_bqg5ymj9">
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="4">
                        <li xml:id="auto_6hrvcw0k">
                            <p xml:id="auto_l9wgk4td">
                                <m>\sqrt{(-6)^2 + 8^2} = \sqrt{36 + 64} = \sqrt{100} = 10</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ucuvcx7v">
                            <p xml:id="auto_r0m9ek07">
                                <m>\sqrt{8^2 + 15^2} = \sqrt{64 + 225} = \sqrt{289} = 17</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_101j4qq3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ldlofaik">
                                <m>\sqrt{(-5)^2 + 12^2} = \sqrt{25 + 144} = \sqrt{169} = 13</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ocx837my">
                            <p xml:id="auto_n3khmidl">
                                <m>\sqrt{3^2 + 7^2} = \sqrt{9 + 49} = \sqrt{58} \approx 7.62</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Provide pre-drawn coordinate planes with vectors already drawn.</li>
                <li>Use colour coding: one colour for horizontal, another for vertical, a third for the vector.</li>
                <li>Provide step-by-step calculation templates with spaces to fill in.</li>
                <li>Allow use of calculators for all calculations.</li>
                <li>Start with vectors that have perfect-square magnitudes (3-4-5, 5-12-13, etc.).</li>
                <li>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Encourage students to create their own magnitude problems.</li>
                <li>Ask students to explain why magnitude is always positive.</li>
                <li>Provide mixed practice with different vector representations.</li>
                <li>Challenge students to find patterns in Pythagorean triples.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Explore three-dimensional vector magnitudes: <m>|\mathbf{v}| = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + z^2}</m>.</li>
                <li>Investigate unit vectors (vectors with magnitude 1).</li>
                <li>Apply magnitudes to real-world distance and speed problems.</li>
                <li>Challenge: If <m>|\mathbf{a}| = 5</m> and <m>|\mathbf{b}| = 3</m>, what are the possible values of <m>|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}|</m>?</li>
                <li>Explore the relationship between magnitude and direction.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity — Navigation and Distance:</alert>
            Work in pairs or small groups. A pilot's flight path is represented as vectors.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>Fly vector <m>\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} 120 \\ 90 \end{pmatrix}</m> (120 km East, 90 km North). Calculate the straight-line distance.</li>
                <li>Then fly vector <m>\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} -50 \\ 60 \end{pmatrix}</m> (50 km West, 60 km North). Calculate this leg's distance.</li>
                <li>Find the total displacement vector <m>\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}</m>.</li>
                <li>Find the straight-line distance from start to finish.</li>
                <li>If average speed is 200 km/h, how long did the entire journey take?</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

